        <h2>SUPERDEBATE COMPETITION</h2>

        <h3>Script 1: Constructive Speech (5 minutes)</h3>

        <div class="script-box">
            <div class="script-header">
                <div class="script-meta">
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Topic:</span>
                        <span>Social media does more harm than good</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Side:</span>
                        <span>Affirmative</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Time:</span>
                        <span>5 minutes</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-content">
                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[0:00]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"In 2019, Facebook's own researchers concluded—and I'm quoting their internal documents—'We make body image issues worse for one in three teenage girls.' The company saw this data. They buried it. This resolution isn't about whether social media could theoretically be better. It's about what social media actually does. I affirm."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">The hook: specific evidence, corporate admission, immediate stakes. Notice: no "Today I will argue" throat-clearing. Jump straight to the strongest opening.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[0:25]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"My first contention: social media is engineered to harm. Not accidentally—deliberately. Former Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya admitted that the platform was designed to exploit 'a vulnerability in human psychology.' Instagram's algorithm promotes the content that generates the strongest emotional reactions—and research consistently shows negative content spreads faster than positive. This isn't a bug. It's the business model."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Contention 1 established with insider evidence and systemic framing. "Engineered to harm" is memorable language judges can flow.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[0:55]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"The evidence is overwhelming. A 2022 study in the Journal of Abnormal Psychology found that rates of depression among U.S. teens increased 63% between 2009 and 2017—precisely tracking smartphone and social media adoption. Correlation isn't causation, my opponent might say. Fine. But Jonathan Haidt's research at NYU controls for confounding variables and still finds a causal link. Teen girls who deactivated Instagram for one month reported significant improvements in body image and life satisfaction."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Preempting the obvious objection (correlation vs causation) and providing response. Evidence hierarchy: peer-reviewed studies, controlled experiments.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[1:40]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"The impact isn't abstract. Youth mental health crisis. Suicide rates among teenage girls have doubled since 2007. The American Psychological Association now treats excessive social media use as a clinical concern. This is the outcome of a system designed to maximize engagement at the cost of wellbeing."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Impact statement with concrete statistics. "The impact isn't abstract" signals to judges: here's why this matters.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[2:05]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"My second contention: social media degrades democracy. A 2020 MIT study found that false news stories are 70% more likely to be shared than true ones. And it's not random—the algorithm actively promotes misinformation because it generates engagement. Russian interference in the 2016 election reached over 126 million Americans through Facebook alone. That's not a communication platform. That's a weapon."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Contention 2: shifts from individual harm to societal harm. Widens the scope of impact. "That's a weapon" is quotable—judges remember vivid language.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[2:45]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"The evidence compounds. Frances Haugen, Facebook whistleblower, testified before Congress that the company knew its platform fueled ethnic violence in Myanmar and political polarization globally—and chose profits over intervention. This isn't about individual bad actors. It's about a system that rewards division."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Building the systemic case. Named whistleblower adds credibility. "Rewards division" ties back to business model argument from Contention 1.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[3:15]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"My third contention: the benefits don't outweigh. My opponent will likely argue that social media connects people. And yes, it can. But the data shows those connections are often shallow and anxiety-inducing. A University of Pittsburgh study found that the more time young adults spent on social media, the more likely they were to feel socially isolated—not less. The connection is illusory. The harm is real."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Preemptive refutation of opponent's likely strongest argument. "The connection is illusory. The harm is real." Memorable contrast.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[3:55]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"They'll say: what about organizing social movements? Fair point. But Black Lives Matter organizers themselves have noted that social media activism often substitutes for real action—slacktivism instead of activism. And platforms regularly suppress organizing when it threatens their bottom line. These aren't reliable tools for change."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Second anticipated objection addressed. Using the opposition's own sources (BLM organizers) strengthens the point.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[4:25]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Let me crystallize. The question isn't whether some good exists on social media. It's whether the net effect is harm or benefit. The evidence is clear: engineered addiction, mental health crisis, democratic erosion, and illusory connection. The harms are documented, systematic, and growing. The benefits are scattered and diminishing."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Summary that reframes the debate on your terms. "Net effect" language sets up the weighing mechanism.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[4:50]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"This is what social media actually does—not what it could do in some hypothetical better world. I urge an affirmative ballot."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Clean close. Final sentence reiterates the frame (actual vs. hypothetical) and asks for the vote.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-analysis">
                <h4>What Made This Work</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Corporate admissions and whistleblower testimony (hard for opponent to dismiss)</li>
                    <li>Three distinct contentions with clear labels</li>
                    <li>Anticipated two likely objections and responded within the constructive</li>
                    <li>Consistent framing: "engineered," "systematic," "documented"—these words recur</li>
                    <li>Strong open and strong close (judges remember first and last impressions)</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>Common Mistake to Avoid</h4>
                <p>Spending too long on definitions. This speech assumes a clear resolution and jumps to substance. Only define terms if they're genuinely contested.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Script 2: Cross-Examination (Examiner)</h3>

        <div class="script-box">
            <div class="script-header">
                <div class="script-meta">
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Context:</span>
                        <span>Following opponent's constructive on same topic (Negative)</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Time:</span>
                        <span>3 minutes</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-content">
                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"You argued that social media enables connection. Who benefits most from these connections?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Opening with a clarifying question. Gets them talking while you assess their strongest ground.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Everyone. People who live far from family. Marginalized communities who find support online. Small businesses..."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Let me focus on one: marginalized communities. Do these communities experience harassment on social media?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Narrowing from their broad claim to a specific, attackable point.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Some do, yes, but the platforms are working on moderation..."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"A yes or no: marginalized communities experience harassment on social media?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Yes."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Got the concession. Now build on it.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"According to the Anti-Defamation League, 41% of Americans have experienced online harassment. Would you say that's consistent with a platform that does 'more good than harm'?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Testing question with evidence. Forces them to defend or concede.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"The harassment happens, but the connection benefits still outweigh—"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"We'll get to weighing. Right now I'm establishing facts. You conceded harassment happens. Let's move to your small business point. Do small businesses on social media pay to reach their own followers?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Control technique: don't let them give speeches. Redirect to facts.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Some use paid promotion, yes."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Right. Organic reach on Facebook for business pages has dropped to about 2%. If you have 1,000 followers, roughly 20 see your post. Unless you pay. Is that a benefit or an extraction system?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">The trap closes: their "benefit" becomes a harm when examined.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"It's still a tool businesses choose to use—"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"A tool they increasingly have to use because customers expect them there. Let me ask about your evidence on social movements. You cited Arab Spring. Did those movements ultimately succeed in establishing stable democracies?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Pivoting to attack their evidence directly. Arab Spring's aftermath undermines the optimistic framing.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"The outcomes varied, but social media played a role in organizing—"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Tunisia is the only country from Arab Spring that remained democratic. The rest: military coups, civil wars, or authoritarian restoration. If social media enables organizing but not sustained success, is it a net benefit or a distraction from real institution-building?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Turning their best example against them. This will be developed in rebuttals.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"I don't think you can blame social media for post-revolutionary failures—"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"I'm not blaming. I'm asking whether the benefit you claimed—organizing—translates to the outcomes you implied. Last question: you said connection is the primary benefit. Do you have evidence that increased social media use correlates with decreased loneliness?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Final question targets the heart of their case. This is what you'll attack in rebuttals.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"The connection is valuable regardless of loneliness metrics—"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"I'll note for the judges that my opponent couldn't provide that evidence. I have studies showing the opposite. Thank you."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Clean exit. Don't gloat—but do flag the gap for judges.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-analysis">
                <h4>What Made This Work</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Every question had a purpose—setup for rebuttals</li>
                    <li>Got clear concessions on harassment and pay-to-play</li>
                    <li>Turned their Arab Spring example against them</li>
                    <li>Exposed a gap in their evidence (loneliness correlation)</li>
                    <li>Maintained control without being aggressive</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>Judge's Perspective</h4>
                <p>Judges want to see efficient, purposeful questioning. This examiner got four usable concessions in three minutes. That's material for rebuttals.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Script 3: Cross-Examination (Being Examined)</h3>

        <div class="script-box">
            <div class="script-header">
                <div class="script-meta">
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Context:</span>
                        <span>You gave the affirmative constructive; opponent is examining</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Time:</span>
                        <span>3 minutes</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-content">
                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"You cited studies about teen depression. Isn't it true that teen depression has many causes beyond social media?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Of course—depression is multifactorial. My argument isn't that social media is the only cause. It's a significant contributing factor, which the evidence I cited demonstrates."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Concede what's obviously true, then hold your ground on the claim you actually made.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Significant contributing factor—can you quantify that? What percentage of teen depression is caused by social media?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"I don't have a precise percentage, and I'd be skeptical of anyone who claims one—these are complex causal systems. What I do have is controlled studies showing that reducing social media use improves outcomes. That's the evidence that matters for this resolution."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Honest about limits, redirect to what you do know. Don't invent data under pressure.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"But if you can't quantify the harm, how can you weigh it against the benefits?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"The same way we weigh most policy tradeoffs—by examining the evidence we have. Controlled studies, internal company research, expert testimony. The question isn't 'can we achieve scientific certainty?' It's 'which direction does the evidence point?' It points toward harm."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Don't accept their frame that uncertainty means you lose. Redirect to evidence quality.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"You mentioned Facebook's internal research. Aren't you cherry-picking the negative findings while ignoring research that shows benefits?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"I'm citing what the company found and tried to hide. If there were equally strong findings showing benefits, Facebook would have published them. The asymmetry in disclosure is telling."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Turn the question: if the evidence for benefits existed, why wasn't it released?</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Are you saying we should ban social media?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Classic overextension trap—trying to make your position sound extreme.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"I'm affirming the resolution as stated: that social media does more harm than good. What policy follows from that is a separate question. This debate is about the factual assessment, not what to do about it."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Stay on the resolution. Don't let them push you into policy positions you haven't argued.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">THEM:</div>
                    <p>"Final question: have you personally benefited from social media?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Sure, in some ways. And I've also seen the harms firsthand. Personal anecdotes don't determine who wins this debate—evidence does."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Honest answer that refuses to let personal experience override the evidence. Judges respect intellectual honesty.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-analysis">
                <h4>What Made This Work</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Answered directly without volunteering extra information</li>
                    <li>Conceded appropriate points (depression is multifactorial) without conceding the argument</li>
                    <li>Refused traps (ban social media, personal anecdote)</li>
                    <li>Maintained composure and confidence throughout</li>
                    <li>Redirected to evidence quality when pushed on uncertainty</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>What to Avoid</h4>
                <p>Getting defensive or argumentative. CX answers should be brief and controlled. Save the arguments for rebuttals.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Script 4: First Rebuttal</h3>

        <div class="script-box">
            <div class="script-header">
                <div class="script-meta">
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Context:</span>
                        <span>Affirmative First Rebuttal after hearing Negative constructive</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Time:</span>
                        <span>3 minutes</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-content">
                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[0:00]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"My opponent's case rests on three claims. Let me show why each one fails, then extend my own case."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Roadmap for judges. They know exactly what's coming.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[0:08]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"First, they argued connection benefits. In cross-examination, they conceded harassment affects marginalized communities—the very people they claim benefit most. They couldn't provide evidence that social media reduces loneliness. In fact, the University of Pittsburgh study I cited shows the opposite: more use correlates with more isolation. The connection they're selling is illusory."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Using CX concessions immediately. This is why good CX matters.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[0:40]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Second, they cited small business benefits. But organic reach has collapsed to 2%—businesses have to pay to reach people who already follow them. That's not a benefit; that's a toll road. And when small businesses become dependent on these platforms, they're vulnerable to algorithm changes that wipe out their visibility overnight. Ask any creator who built an audience on YouTube or Facebook about what happens when the algorithm shifts."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Turning their argument: "benefit" becomes harm when examined closely.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[1:15]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Third, social movements. They cited Arab Spring. One democracy survived—Tunisia. The rest: Syria, Libya, Egypt—civil war, military rule, or authoritarian restoration. If social media helps people organize but doesn't help them sustain change, is that a benefit? Or is it a distraction from the hard work of institution-building? At best, it's neutral. More likely, it creates the illusion of progress while undermining the real thing."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Their strongest example, thoroughly reframed. Notice: not denying social media played a role, but questioning whether that role was net-positive.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[1:55]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Now let me extend my case. My opponent didn't deny that platforms are engineered for engagement over wellbeing. They didn't contest the mental health data. They didn't challenge the misinformation research. These arguments flow through."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Critical move: identify what they dropped. Dropped arguments are conceded arguments.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[2:15]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"They did say depression has many causes—and I agreed. But that doesn't negate my argument. Smoking isn't the only cause of lung cancer, but it's still harmful. The question isn't whether social media is the only problem. It's whether it makes things worse. The evidence says yes."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Responding to their best attack on your case. The smoking analogy is concrete and memorable.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you"><span class="script-timestamp">[2:40]</span> YOU:</div>
                    <p>"The weighing is straightforward. My harms are documented, systematic, and growing. Their benefits are contested, diminishing, and in some cases, actually harms in disguise. I urge an affirmative ballot."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Clean close with clear weighing. "Harms in disguise" references the turns you executed.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-analysis">
                <h4>What Made This Work</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Clear structure: attack their three points, extend yours</li>
                    <li>Used CX concessions as evidence</li>
                    <li>Turned two of their three arguments</li>
                    <li>Identified and noted their drops</li>
