        <h3>Script 6: Disagreeing with Your Boss in a Meeting</h3>

        <div class="script-box">
            <div class="script-header">
                <div class="script-meta">
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Context:</span>
                        <span>Team meeting; boss proposes rushing a product launch</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="script-meta-item">
                        <span class="script-meta-label">Stakes:</span>
                        <span>Technical debt, team burnout, your credibility</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-content">
                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">BOSS:</div>
                    <p>"I want us to push the launch up two weeks. The market window is now—if we wait, we lose momentum."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"I understand the urgency, and I share the goal of hitting this market window. Can I share some data that might affect how we approach the timing?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Acknowledge their goal first. Ask permission to contribute—not to disagree, but to add information.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">BOSS:</div>
                    <p>"Sure, go ahead."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Our QA backlog right now is 47 tickets, and about 12 of those are high-severity. If we launch in two weeks, we'll ship with known issues that affect core workflows. The competitor we're trying to beat launched early last quarter and spent three months in recovery mode—their reviews tanked and they're still rebuilding trust."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Specific data, not vague concerns. Relevant precedent that shows the risk.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">BOSS:</div>
                    <p>"We can patch critical issues after launch. That's what updates are for."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Absolutely, we can patch. The question is whether launch-day reviews and first impressions are recoverable. First-week reviews on the App Store are weighted heavily. A buggy launch could mean we're fighting a 3.2-star rating for months."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Don't argue that patching is impossible—argue that the damage happens before the patch.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">BOSS:</div>
                    <p>"So what are you proposing?"</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"A middle path: we launch in three weeks instead of four, which still captures the window, but gives QA time to close the high-severity issues. And we do a soft launch to a smaller segment first—1% of users. If it's stable, we roll out fully. If not, we fix before the broader audience sees it."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Offer a solution, not just objections. The "middle path" frame makes it easier to accept.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">BOSS:</div>
                    <p>"The soft launch idea might work. Let me think about it."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Happy to pull together the data on our last two launches—what went well and what cost us. Might help inform the decision."</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Offer to do homework that supports your position. Make it easy for them to agree.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-analysis">
                <h4>What Made This Work</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Opened by aligning with their goal, not opposing their idea</li>
                    <li>Specific data (47 tickets, 12 high-severity) not vague concern</li>
                    <li>Relevant precedent (competitor's failed early launch)</li>
                    <li>Offered a concrete alternative, not just objections</li>
                    <li>Ended by offering to do additional work—demonstrates commitment</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>What to Avoid</h4>
                <p>"That won't work because..." in front of the team. Private pushback is safer; public pushback requires more diplomacy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

