                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">ENGINEERING:</div>
                    <p>"...It's a subset. We could do database-level isolation without the full architecture. That's probably 6-8 weeks, not 6 months."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"So the path might be: database-level isolation for Q2 to close Johnson, with full multi-tenant on the roadmap for Q4. Sales, does that meet Johnson's actual requirement? Engineering, does that timeline work technically?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Propose the solution that emerges from their own constraints. Make both sides say yes to specifics.</div>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">SALES:</div>
                    <p>"If the isolation is real and we can show documentation, yes."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line them">
                    <div class="script-speaker them">ENGINEERING:</div>
                    <p>"6 weeks if we can freeze the rest of the Q2 roadmap. We can't do both."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="script-line you">
                    <div class="script-speaker you">YOU:</div>
                    <p>"Got it. So the tradeoff is: win Johnson but push two other Q2 features to Q3. Let me take that tradeoff to leadership with the numbers and get a decision by Friday. Does that work for both of you?"</p>
                    <div class="script-annotation">Escalate clearly when needed. Don't try to make a decision above your authority—but do prepare the decision for those who can.</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="script-analysis">
                <h4>What Made This Work</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Reframed from "feature debate" to "what does the customer actually need"</li>
                    <li>Got engineering to propose a faster solution themselves</li>
                    <li>Made both parties say yes to specific commitments</li>
                    <li>Escalated the tradeoff clearly when it exceeded your authority</li>
                    <li>Set a timeline for resolution (Friday)</li>
                </ul>
                <h4>What to Avoid</h4>
                <p>Taking sides. Your job is to find the path forward, not to prove Sales or Engineering wrong.</p>
            </div>
